There is a race condition in CursorStream which prevents the stream from detecting that it was paused, causing it to continue sending data events.

In this scenario, the user uses the data event handler to pause and resume the stream.

When the data event handler is first called, the stream will be paused. However, since the event handler is called after that _next() will be called, the stream will continue emitting the next data event. And, with the event handler eventually resuming the stream, this continues until all events in the stream have been consumed.

There is a rather simple patch to this, which moves the guard

  if (this.paused || this._destroyed) return;

from the top of the _next method into the process.nextTick 
handler that is installed by the same method, e.g.

  // Get the next object
  process.nextTick(function() {
    if (this.paused || this._destroyed) return;
    self._cursor.nextObject(function (err, doc) {
      self._onNextObject(err, doc);
    });
  });

Doing so solved the race condition for at least my specific use case
and it might solve the same race condition for other use cases as well.

On my machine it takes about 10% per cursor. Adding mor cursors adds more load, up to 50%.

