Attempting to save() a document with _id:0 results in a duplicate key error if a document already exists with that _id.  I suspect it is not detecting the presence of _id:0 and trying to do an insert instead of upsert.

Demonstration:

    require('mongodb').Db.connect("mongodb://localhost/test", function(err, client) {
      client.collection('test', function (err, collection) {
        collection.remove({}, {safe: true}, function (err, result) {
          collection.save({'_id': 0, 'name': 'foo'}, {safe: true}, function (err, result) {
            console.log("saved: " + result);
            collection.save({'_id': 0, 'name': 'foo'}, {safe: true}, function (err, result) {
              client.close();
              if (err) return console.error(err);
              else console.log("saved: " + result);
            });
          });
        });
      });
    });

I was benchmarking our node application using a 3-node mongo replication cluster, and I found that as he number of concurrent connections grows, and some of them start to fail, these 'failed' connections remain in some sort of 'open' state. As I ramp up the concurrent requests, I see more and more of the following errors:

{code}
Error: No primary found in set
    at  node_modules/mongodb/lib/mongodb/connection/repl_set/repl_set.js:419:45
... snipped ...
{code}
{code}
Error: Could not locate any valid servers in initial seed list
    at node_modules/mongodb/lib/mongodb/mongo_client.js:281:52
... snipped ...
{code}
{code}
Error: No valid replicaset instance servers found
    at  node_modules/mongodb/lib/mongodb/connection/repl_set/repl_set.js:416:45
... snipped ...
{code}

Looking at the output from mongostat, it seems that these failed connections remain in some sort of 'open' state

{code}
conn    set             repl  time
332     EUMongoCluster  SEC   14:48:06
{code}

and don't get terminated until the nodejs process exits. So as we begin to get 'failed' connections, the pool fills up with these and so the application can't make any new connections (I'm making assumptions about the structure here, based on what I can see happening, I don't know if there is a pool). The only way to kill these connections is to quit the nodejs process.

I've tested this with v1.3.10 and 1.3.12 of the driver, on Mac and Ubuntu and see the same behaviour.

To connect, I'm using mongoClient.connect() and specifying the following url: {code}mongodb://192.168.10.71:27017,192.168.10.72:27017,192.168.10.73:27017/Restaurants?replicaSet=EUMongoCluster;connectTimeoutMS=300000;safe=true;readPreference=secondaryPreferred;maxLifeTimeMS=60000{code}

Where *.10.71 is the primary and *.10.72/73 are the secondaries.

